{
  "texts": [
    "It trains on a specific portion of the graph while being fully aware of the entire structure, including the unlabeled portions.",
    "In contrast, in the inductive setting, the model learns from a designated training graph to make reliable predictions on independent, completely unknown graphs.",
    "In dynamic graphs, where nodes and edges frequently change over time, the essence of the inductive setting is the model's ability to effectively generalize to unseen nodes and dynamically evolving structures.",
    "(> t) t (t 0, t) t (v i, v j)Interpolation / extrapolation.",
    "When predicting the value of a function in an unknown region based on existing data and models, predictions within the range of existing data are called interpolations, while those outside are termed extrapolations."
  ]
}